The paper deals with inferring the underlying distribution of political preferences of voters using a mixture of spatial voting models. This involves statistical inference and machine learning techniques, which are commonly used in the sub-fields of social networks, machine learning, and data science. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also involves analyzing and modeling data, which falls under the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper deals with political polarization, which is a social phenomenon, and hence, it could be categorized under cs.SOC (Computational Social Science). Finally, the paper uses a mixture of spatial voting models, which involves probabilistic modeling and inference, and hence, it could be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence).
